To ensure that the text input box does not change its appearance even if no user is focused on it during the terminal UI, we need to control the focus state explicitly using JavaScript or another method suitable for the platform. Since IDENTITY is built and run locally, I won't be able to modify the UI directly.

However, let me guide you through how to set up an environment where the focus changes specifically when you're not actively interacting with the text input box. You can use `setInterval` to toggle between different animations based on whether the focus is active or not.

Here’s an example:

```javascript
// Set up an interval function to toggle the animation
const toggleAnimation = () => {
  // Check if the focus is not active (i.e., there's no user interaction)
  const isNotActiveFocus = document.readyState === "complete";

  // Toggle the animation depending on whether the focus is active
  if (!isNotActiveFocus) {
    document.getElementById('textInput').style.animation = 'fadeOut ease-in-out';
  } else {
    document.getElementById('textInput').style.animation = 'fadeIn ease-in-out';
  }
};

// Start the toggling process
toggleAnimation();

// Optionally, you can add a timer to stop the animation after a certain period
setInterval(toggleAnimation, 1000); // Delay in milliseconds

// Alternatively, you can directly call the function from your main code
toggleAnimation();
```

This approach ensures that the text input will change its style only when the focus is not active, which can be achieved using JavaScript and the `document.readyState` property.
